HAL Code Concept
// 1. Set Window (e.g. 0x2A Column Addr)
uint8_t cmd = 0x2A; 
HAL_GPIO_WritePin(DC_PORT, DC_PIN, GPIO_PIN_RESET); // Command
HAL_SPI_Transmit(&hspi1, &cmd, 1, 10);

// Coordinates are 16-bit: [StartMSB, StartLSB, EndMSB, EndLSB]
uint8_t params[] = {
    x0 &gt;&gt; 8, x0 & 0xFF,  // Start Column
    x1 &gt;&gt; 8, x1 & 0xFF   // End Column
};
HAL_GPIO_WritePin(DC_PORT, DC_PIN, GPIO_PIN_SET);   // Data
HAL_SPI_Transmit(&hspi1, params, 4, 10);

// 2. Initiate Write (0x2C) & Start DMA
cmd = 0x2C;
HAL_GPIO_WritePin(DC_PORT, DC_PIN, GPIO_PIN_RESET); // Command Mode
HAL_SPI_Transmit(&hspi1, &cmd, 1, 10);

HAL_GPIO_WritePin(DC_PORT, DC_PIN, GPIO_PIN_SET);   // Data Mode
HAL_SPI_Transmit_DMA(&hspi1, pixel_buffer, buffer_size);

Crucial: Accessing the SPI peripheral while DMA is busy will cause an error.
Fix: Always check hspi1.State or wait for the callback.

Stepper: HAL Implementation
// Define Pins (ULN2003 inputs)
#define IN1_PIN GPIO_PIN_0
// ... and so on ...

void Stepper_SetStep(uint8_t s1, uint8_t s2, uint8_t s3, uint8_t s4) {
    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOA, IN1_PIN, s1);
    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOA, IN2_PIN, s2);
    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOA, IN3_PIN, s3);
    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOA, IN4_PIN, s4);
}

// Timer ISR (Handles the Sequence)
static uint8_t step_index = 0;
switch(step_index % 4) {
    case 0: Stepper_SetStep(1, 0, 0, 0); break;
    case 1: Stepper_SetStep(0, 1, 0, 0); break;
    case 2: Stepper_SetStep(0, 0, 1, 0); break;
    case 3: Stepper_SetStep(0, 0, 0, 1); break;
}
step_index++; // Move to next step

Deep Dive: SPI & DMA
The Problem: CPU Overhead

Sending 115,200 bytes using HAL_SPI_Transmit() (blocking) wastes huge CPU cycles.
The CPU sits idle waiting for the shift register to empty.

The Solution: DMA (Direct Memory Access)

CPU Action: “Hey DMA Controller, take these 512 bytes from memory address 0x2000... and shove them into SPI1-&gt;DR register.”
DMA Action: Moves data byte-by-byte automatically.
CPU Freedom: CPU returns to main() immediately to compute the next batch of pixels.
Completion: DMA triggers an interrupt (Transfer Complete) when done.

In Our Code
// CPU sets it up...
HAL_SPI_Transmit_DMA(&hspi1, buffer, size); 

// ...and walks away!
// (Though in our simplified while loop, we wait for it to finish 
// before sending the next chunk to avoid overwriting the buffer).

